Disk Forensics > [T7]: Connected Devices Forensics: Exploring Registry

(1) Registry

SYSTEM Hive

Most of the information we look after resides in the registry SYSTEM hive. Here is a list of what keys to check, followed by explaining the information to expect in each key.

  • HKLM\SYSTEM\ControlSet001\Enum\USB
  • HKLM\SYSTEM\ControlSet001\Enum\USBSTOR
  • HKLM\SYSTEM\ControlSet001\Enum\SWD\WPDBUSENUM
  • HKLM\SYSTEM\ControlSet001\Control\DeviceClasses
  • HKLM\SYSTEM\MountedDevices

 

Let's start by opening Registry Explorer, loading the SYSTEM hive, and checking the first key, "HKLM\SYSTEM\ControlSet001\Enum\USB".

 

"USB" key - (zoom in)

This key contains information about all USB devices connected to the system, anything from a USB mouse to a storage device.

  1. The "USB" registry key.
  2. The "USB" registry key path.
  3. A sub-key for each USB device is named after the device's Vendor ID (VID) and Product ID (PID). For example, the third device VID is "0781," and PID is "55A9".
  4. Parsed information for each sub-key. 
    • Last write time of that registry key.
    • The "key name" contains the VID and PID values of the USB device. You can search with VID and PID in the figure to determine the USB manufacturer. Check out this link, and you will see that the above VID and PID are for a SANDISK device.
    • Device serial number.
    • Description.
    • The port the USB device was connected to.
  5. Each row contains information about one device under the USB key. For example, the fourth/highlighted row on the right side corresponds to the fourth sub-key under "USB" on the left side (the one starting with VID_078).
 

Moving to the second key, "USBSTOR," which stores information about USB data drives. For example, a USB mouse will not appear in that key because it's not a data drive. In fact, USBSTOR is an abbreviation for USB Storage.

 

USBSTOR key - (zoom in)


1: USBSTOR key.
2,3 and 4: A sub-sub-key for each device.
5: Parsed information for all devices listed under the "USBSTOR" key, one row for each device.
6: The details of the first device under the "USBSTOR" key. The first column shows the timestamp of the last write to this registry sub-key. The remaining columns display device-related information. You can calculate for how long the device was connected to the system (last time) by substracting "Last connected" from "Last removed".

 

Important note about serial numbers: by definition, a serial number is a unique identifier assigned incrementally or sequentially to an item, to uniquely identify it, set by the device manufacturer, and printed on the device surface. We will refer to this as MGSN (manufacturer-generated serial number). This serial number is hardcoded and never changes. Check out this link.
 
From a forensic perspective, the MGSN should be the same serial number you see in the registry. However, sometimes, Windows cannot fetch the USB device's serial number assigned by the manufacturer (MGSN). In that case, windows assign a random serial number that changes every time the device is formatted. We will refer to it as WGSN (windows-generated serial number).

 

We have done some research to determine the impact of both scenarios on artifacts. The conclusion of our research is:

  1. There is no fixed format for serial numbers in both cases (MGSN and WGSN). They come in different lengths and compositions (i.e., numeric only, alpha-numeric...etc).
  2. The most common shapes of serial numbers are:
    • Case 1: a string that does not contain the "&" sign. Example:" 01012f4.......72dedac1" as shown in the screenshot above.
    • Case 2: A string that contains the "&" sign only at the end (second to last char). Example: "0701083A......&0".
    • Case 3: A string that contains the "&" sign at the beginning (second char). Example: "1&9080.....".
 
The consistent interpretation we have seen so far is that the SN in the registry matches the MGSN only in case #3. Other than that, Windows generates a random serial number. You may wonder, why should you care about that? A common scenario is having more than one analyst working on the same investigation. One may use the MGSN, while the other uses WGSN to identify the evidence. So, you have to be aware of such discrepancies.

 

The good news is that it does not matter which SN exists in the registry from a forensic analysis point of view because it will be consistent in all artifacts across the system. After all, a serial number is supposed to be a unique identifier. That means you can use the serial number identified in the registry to find other relevant artifacts on the system (check out the following video). 

 

Let's move on to the third key, "WPDBUSENUM".

WPDBUSENUM key - (zoom in)

  1. WPDBUSENUM registry key.
  2. WPDBUSENUM registry key path.
  3. A sub-key for each USB drive.
  4. Most of the information present here can be found in the previous keys discussed above. Except for the "FriendlyName," the name assigned to this drive in Windows.

 

Another key to check under the SYSTEM hive is "DeviceClasses".

DeviceClasses - (zoom in)

This is an important key to check because it will have a trace for any connected device (not only USB). Popular examples that you may find under this key are iSCSI hard disks, printers, Firewire, Bluetooth, and webcams. 

  1. DeviceClasses registry key.
  2. DeviceClasses registry key path.
  3. A sub-key for each connected device in the form of GUID. You can find a list of GUID-to-device type mapping here.
  4. Each sub-key under "DeviceClasses" from the left will have a record on the right side showing device information. As you may notice, the type column includes different devices, not only USB.

The last key to check under the SYSTEM hive is "MountedDevices."

MountedDevices key - (zoom in)

This key contains the assigned letter and Volume GUID for each connected device.

  1. MountedDevices key.
  2. MountedDevices key path
  3. The "Device Name" column will include the volume GUID and assigned drive letter. The "Device Data" column contains the device type, name, vendor ID, product ID, and serial number.

Almost all device artifacts can be found under the SYSTEM hive. However, there are a couple of other registry keys that will have relevant information, too, such as:

  • SOFTWARE Hive
    • Microsoft\Windows Portable Devices\Devices 
    • Microsoft\Windows Search\VolumeInfoCache
  • Amcache Hive
    • Root\InventoryDevicePnp
